In order to simplify mqtt callbacks and keep the original on_message callback as clean and readable as possible, there is a callback mechanism which helps users generate callbacks in a simple fashion as shown below.  
```
@CallbackMechanism.make_callback(&quot;client1&quot;, &quot;topic.split(&#39;/&#39;)[1] == &#39;callback&#39;&quot;)
def callback_trigger(topic, payload):
    print(&quot;callback has been triggered&quot;)  
    print(&quot;do something&quot;)
```

The above decorator takes first argument as mqtt client id on which the user wants the callback to be triggered and the following argument is an expression which if evaluated true triggers the callback. If a service/module consists of a multiple callbacks which are to be triggered from different conditions, this makes generating callbacks simple and clean from the user&#39;s perspective.  
  
Callback mechanism is a class which wraps the original on_message callback function which makes it quite flexible for the user to either use the mechanism to generate callbacks or trigger callbacks from the original on_message function which again might lead to multiple if/else conditions and a complicated function, just saying. 

**Callback Mechanism**  
```
class CallbackMechanism:

    callbackFunctionsTriggers = {}

    @classmethod
    def wrap_on_message(cls, on_message_func):
        def wrapped_on_message(*args):
            client = args[0]
            msg = args[2]
            clientId = str(client._client_id)[2:-1]
            topic = msg.topic
            payload = str(msg.payload)[2:-1]
            on_message_func(topic, payload)
            for condition, callback in cls.callbackFunctionsTriggers[
                    clientId].items():
                if eval(condition):
                    callback(topic, payload)
        return wrapped_on_message

    @classmethod
    def make_callback(cls, clientId, condition):
        def decorator(callbackFunc):
            if clientId not in cls.callbackFunctionsTriggers:
                cls.callbackFunctionsTriggers[clientId] = {}
            cls.callbackFunctionsTriggers[clientId][condition] = callbackFunc

            return callbackFunc

        return decorator
```

**User**  

```
@CallbackMechanism.wrap_on_message
def on_message(topic, payload):
    print(&quot;topic --&gt; &quot;, topic)
    print(&quot;payload --&gt; &quot;, payload)
    print(&quot;do anything&quot;)

@CallbackMechanism.make_callback(&quot;client1&quot;, &quot;topic.split(&#39;/&#39;)[1] == &#39;callback&#39;&quot;)
def callback_trigger(topic, payload):
    print(&quot;callback has been triggered&quot;)  
    print(&quot;do something&quot;)
```  

1. if there are say 20-30 callbacks which need to be triggered from different conditions based on different topics and payloads, the original on_message function will be polluted with complicated if/else and will become a lengthy function. What are your thoughts about the above mechanism ? Can there be a better approach for the problem of complications of multiple callback conditions and their calling inside a single function ?  
